  "derivation_layer": {
    "source_latex": "% BEGIN TZP DERIVATION LAYER\n\\tzpsection{Derivation Layer}\n\\paragraph{Primary Equation.}\n\\begin{equation}\n\\exists D\n\\quad\\text{such that}\\quad\nP(D\\mid H)\\neq P(D\\mid \\neg H).\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Primary Derivation.}\nA hypothesis $H$ is falsifiable only if there exists some possible observation $D$ that would distinguish $H$ from its negation.\n\nIf every possible observation had equal probability under both $H$ and $\\neg H$, then no data could discriminate between them:\n\n\\begin{equation}\nP(D\\mid H)=P(D\\mid \\neg H)\n\\quad\n\\text{for all }D .\n\\end{equation}\n\nTherefore, falsifiability requires at least one possible discriminating datum:\n\n\\begin{equation}\n\\boxed{\n\\exists D\n\\quad\\text{such that}\\quad\nP(D\\mid H)\\neq P(D\\mid \\neg H).\n}\n\\end{equation}\n\n\\paragraph{Interpretation.}\nA Trawinistic hypothesis must produce at least one observational consequence that differs from its negation.\n% END TZP DERIVATION LAYER"
  },
